.pl 62
                            Chapter 7


                    INVOCATION AND OPERATION


7.1  INPUT AND OUTPUT FILES USED/GENERATED BY AS

AS  assembles the user's source file and generates an object file 
and an optional listing file. A cross reference may be optionally 
obtained producing a third temporary file.

Source  file  - Input.  The source program is contained  in  this 
file, AS assumes an extension of .A32.

Object  file - Output.  The object file contains the output  code 
from the assembler.  The object file may be linked or placed into 
a  library via the librarian.  The object file is given  the .O32 
extension.

Listing  file  - Output.  The listing file  contains  the  source 
program in addition to the text produced by the AS assembler. The 
list file is given a .L32 extension.

Errors - Output.  The errors from the assembler are printed below 
the  line which gave an error in the list file.  The  errors  are 
also  displayed  on the console during assembly  time.  They  may 
optionally be re-directed to a disk file by typing:

AS  [{-L | -X | -V | -W}] 
               <src_file> > <err_file>

7.2  AS ASSEMBLER INVOCATION

The  Assembler  is  invoked by typing AS followed by any  of  the 
required  switches  and the source filename.  The  switches  must 
appear before the filename and be preceded by a minus sign. If no 
filename  is specified,  AS terminates.   The extension  .A32  is 
assumed by AS and must not be specified.
.pa
Examples:

	1. AS
	2. AS  TEST
	3. AS -L TEST
        4. AS -X TEST
Example 1 doesn't specify a filename and thus the assembler  will 
terminate.

Example  2 will assemble the source file TEST.A32 and produce and 
object file with the name: TEST.O32.

Example 3 will assemble the source file TEST.A32 and produce both 
an  object  file and a listing file with the names  TEST.O32  and 
TEST.L32 respectively.

Example 4 will assemble the source file TEST.A32 and produce both 
an  object file and a listing file as in example 3,  but it  will 
append a full cross reference at the end of the list file.

7.3  ASSEMBLER OUTPUT LISTING

Figure 7-1 shows a sample assembly program.  The listing produced 
by the Assembler is shown in Figure 7-2.

Figure  7-3 shows a sample program with several errors. (Table 7-
2 gives a description of assembly errors).

7.4  AS ASSEMBLY ERRORS

Assembler  errors are identified in the listing file by an  error 
number  and a '^' in the vicinity of the error.  The line  number 
and  the  error message is also displayed on the  console  during 
assembly time.

Figure 7-4 shows an example of a listing file with some errors.


.pa
               TABLE 7-1  OPTIONAL SWITCHES SYNTAX



AS [-L | -X] <src_file> [> <err_file> ]

	-L
		- Produce  assembler listing.  No listing is  the 
                  default. List file name is <src_file>.L32

	-X
                 - Produce  cross  referenced listing.  No  cross 
                   reference is the default. The cross referenced 
                   file is named <src_file>.L32

        -V
                 - Increase  the  symbol  table space  for  local 
                   symbols  within  a  procedure  to  the  amount 
                   specified after the -V.  The assembler by  the 
                   default  sets  up enough space for  200  local 
                   symbols.

         -W 
                 - Specify  that  the assembler is to use 16  bit 
                   word  displacements  as against  32  bits  for 
                   unresolved forward references.
                   
	> <err_file>

		 - Log any errors in <err_file>.
		   no log file is the default.

.pa
                     EXPORTP	XYZ
                     EXPORT	TEST,FRED
                     START	TEST
                     BLKB	10
             TEST:   MOVB	R0,R1
             FRED:   MOVB	R7,R7
                     BR	        TEST
             XYZ:    BYTE	'THIS IS A TEST'

                     Figure	7.1  Example 32000 source




