                            Appendix B
                         PSUEDO-OP SUMMARY

A  summary  of  all the DSI-32000 Assembler pseudo-ops  is  given 
below:

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Symbol Generation
-----------------------------------------------------------------

<symbol>:[:| -] EQU <expression>
                    assigns  <symbol>  the  type   and  value  of 
                    <expression>.  The symbol is either local (:) 
                    or public (::, :-).

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Data Generation
-----------------------------------------------------------------

[<label>] BYTE [[<repetition-factor>]] {<expression> | <string>}
                    generate either byte constant(s) or a string. 
                    <repetition-factor>   specifies   number   of 
                    occurrences of value.

[<label>] SBYTE [[<repetition-factor]] {<expression> | <string>} ,,,
                    generate  either byte constant(s) or  string. 
                    <repetition-factor>   specifies   number   of 
                    occurrences of value.

[<label>] WORD [[<repetition-factor]] <expression>,,,
                    generates   word   constants.    <expression> 
                    specifies constant value.

[<label>] SWORD [[<repetition-factor]] <expression>,,,
                    generates   word   constants.    <expression> 
                    specifies constant value.

[<label] DOUBLE [[<repetition-factor]] <expression>,,,
                    generates double-word constants.

[<label>] SDOUBLE [[repetition-factor>]] <expression>,,,
                    generates double-word constants.

[<label>] FLOAT [[<repetition-factor>]] <expression>,,,
                    generates   single-precision   floating-point 
                    constants.

[<label>] LONG [[<repetition-factor>]] <expression> ,,,
                    generates   double-precision   floating-point 
                    constants.
.pa
[<label>] FIELD [<subfield-length>] <subfield-value> ,,,
                    generates   bit   fields.   <subfield-length> 
                    specifies length of  field.  <subfield-value> 
                    specifies field value.

[<label>] IF <expression1> [<operator> <expression2>]
                    if  the result is true then source  following 
                    the IF is assembled.

[<label>] ENDIF     terminates the corresponding IF

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Storage Allocation
-----------------------------------------------------------------

[<label>] BLKB [<expression>]
                    allocates  consecutive  bytes of  memory  for 
                    storage. <expression> specifies the number of 
                    bytes.

[<label>] BLKW [<expression>]
                    allocates  consecutive  words of  memory  for 
                    storage. <expression> specifies the number of 
                    words.

[<label>] BLKD [<expression>]
                    allocates  consecutive double-words of memory 
                    for  storage.   <expression>  specifies   the 
                    number of double-words.

[<label>] BLKF [<expression>]
                    allocates consectuve double-words for single-
                    precision       floating-point       storage.
                    <expression>  specifies the number of double-
                    words.

[<label>] BLKL [<expression>]
                    allocates consecutive quad-words for  double-
                    precision       floating-point       storage. 
                    <expression>  specifies  the number of  quad-
                    words.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Listing Control
-----------------------------------------------------------------

[<label>] TITLE <string>
                    prints  the specified <string> at the top  of 
                    each page of the listing file.
.pa
[<label>] SUBTITLE <string>
                    prints  the specified <string> at the top  of 
                    each  page of the listing file and below  the 
                    title string (if any).

[<label>]  NOLIST   suppresses the printing of source  statements 
                    to the listing file.

[<label>] LIST      restores the printing of source statements to
                    the listing file.

[<label>] EJECT     causes the listing to continue at the top  of 
                    the next page.

[<label>] WIDTH <expression>
                    performs  no function.  It is supported to be 
                    compatible with other assemblers.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Linkage Control
-----------------------------------------------------------------

IMPORT <symbol> ,,,
                    assigns   external  type  to  the   specified 
                    <symbol>.   <symbol>  must  be  defined  with 
                    public  scope in some module of the  program. 
                    For use with data.

IMPORTP <symbol> ,,,
                    assigns   external  type  to  the   specified 
                    <symbol>.   <symbol>  must  be  defined  with 
                    public  scope in some module of the  program. 
                    For use with procedures.

EXPORT <symbol> ,,,
                    assigns   public  scope  to   the   specified 
                    <symbol>.  <symbol>  must  be defined in  the 
                    current module. For use with data.

EXPORTP <symbol> ,,,
                    assigns   public  scope  to   the   specified 
                    <symbol>.  <symbol>  must  be defined in  the 
                    current module. For use with procedures.

COMM    <symbol>, length
                    imports a symbol of specified length.  If the 
                    symbol is not resolved in another module then 
                    the linker will allocate space for the symbol 
                    in a dummy module.
.pa
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Segment Control
-----------------------------------------------------------------

INITFUN             special   directive   for  the   Green   Hill 
                    compilers   to  allow  initialising  external 
                    variables.

DSECT               sets  location counter to IM relocation  mode 
                    with 0 offset.

PROGRAM [<expression>]
                    set  location  counter to PC relocation  mode 
                    with offset specified by <expression>.  If no 
                    <expression>  is specified,  offset  is  next 
                    available program code address.

STATIC              sets  location counter to SB relocation  mode 
                    with  offset  zero or to the  next  available 
                    static base address.

LOC  <expression>   sets  location counter to the relocation mode 
                    and offset specified by <expression>.

ENDSEG              terminates   current  segment  and   restores 
                    location  counter to previous relocation mode 
                    and offset.

ALIGN <expression1>, [<expression2>]
                    set location counter offset to a multiple  of 
                    <expression1>  or  the sum of a  multiple  of 
                    <expression1>  and  <expresion2>.  Relocation 
                    mode remains unchanged.

-----------------------------------------------------------------
Module Control
-----------------------------------------------------------------

MODULE <symbol>     assigns  the name  <symbol>  to  the  current 
                    module.

START <expression>  sets   the    execution   start  address   to 
                    <expression>.   <expression>  must  have   PC 
                    relocation mode.
.pa
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Procedure Management
-----------------------------------------------------------------

<label>  PROC       specifies  the  start of a procedure and  the 
                    procedure's    parameter    block.    <label> 
                    specifies procedure's name.

RETURNS             specifies  the start of a procedure's  return 
                    value block.

VAR  [<reglist>]    specifies the  start of a  procedure's  local 
                    variable  block and saves the General-Purpose 
                    registers specfied by <reglist>. <reglist> is 
                    optional.

BEGIN               specifies   the   start    of   a   procedure 
                    instruction block.

ENDPROC             terminates a procedure.
.pa
.cw 10
